<br>
Seems to me we'd need a forge, 1 vault, gh porter, all right off the bat.  Since we can bind in gh (or sauvage if I read correctly) and portal directly to the GH a bind isn't really that important atm.<br>
<br>
I'm looking at a setup for a craft-house and rvr-house (rvr -&gt; cottage) as it's easier on the brain <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    Also it's the logical place for a lathe and you need a wood merchant for RvR so...all kinda falls together on that level too (I think).  Hidien's idea of vaulted rams sounds like a better plan than a siege merchant.  With 100 slots we can easily keep a good 10 rams in the siege locker there.<br>
<br>
What we've spent so far:<br>
1plat - forge<br>
0plat - spellcraft/alc table (donation)<br>
0plat - spellcraft merchant (donation)<br>
1plat - guild vault (1)<br>
~650gold - upgrades to facing of the guild houses, placing of emblems.<br>
100g - portal to GH merchant<br>
<br>
<br>
So large ammenities...there are 3 hookpoints in the cottage, 4 in the house for merchants and such.  So let's see what we need NPC-wise:<br>
<br>
Healer <br>
GH porter<br>
Albion Vault<br>
Border Portal Keep Teleporter <br>
Apprentice Tradeskills Merchant &lt;- this assumes that that wood for ram construction and door repair aren't located on the GM merchant)<br>
Grandmaster Tradeskills Merchant <br>
Spellcrafting Merchant <br>
Alchemy Merchants (2 sets of two merchants, configured differently ) <br>
<br>
That's 9 and we have 7...methinks we're 2 hookpoints shy.<br>
<br>
Now, two ways to look at this:<br>
1) Our alliancemates have some of these featuers and we can use their equipment (but can make making ram parts a bit annoying)<br>
2) We keep 2 of them locked in a vault and exchange them out as needed.  Caveat to this is that apparently <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>you can not delegate the ability to place tools or NPCs</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> so only the house-owner can do it.<br>
<br>
Now the healer/albion vault are pefect for this as they'd prolly be in the basement anyway but I can't think of any other 'exchangables' that won't mess something up someplace.<br>
<br>
Seems to me that the priority to get these in would be:<br>
1) Spellcraft merch (paid for)<br>
2) GH Porter (have) <br>
3) Alb Vault<br>
4) Grandmaster Tradeskills Merchant <br>
5) Apprentice Tradeskills Merchant<br>
6) Alc 1<br>
7) Alc 2<br>
Healer<br>
BK Porter  <br>
(Healer isn't relevant w/o a BK porter b/c if you port to GH you can use the healer there)<br>
<br>
I see no need for a consignment merchant either as only the guildleader rank can use the dern thing -- but make a case if you think it could be useful.<br>
<br>
NPCs we don't <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>need</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
Hastener <br>
Smith <br>
Enchanter <br>
Emblemeer <br>
Recharger <br>
Capital City Teleporter <br>
Border Non-portal Keep Teleporter *<br>
Siegecraft Supplies Merchant *<br>
* would be cool to have<br>
<br>
Keep in mind we can get other NPCs but they'd have to be swapped out by either by someone with guildleader rank for the guild house or the house-owner for the cottage (We've the treasury-bot there who owns the cottage and holds guildleader rank but that doesn't help if neither Rhi or I are on)<br>
<br>
So let's look at NPC pricing:<br>
1) 0 cost to guild (member donation)<br>
2) 0 cost to guild (purchased already)<br>
3) 100g<br>
4) 500g<br>
5) 100g<br>
6) 100g<br>
7) 100g<br>
(healer) 3plat<br>
(snow port) 500g<br>
<br>
Net: 900g<br>
(opt) 4plat, 400g<br>
<br>
Bindstone...I can see this being useful in RvR but I can see it being a royal pain in the ass too.  It's really only good for RvR purposes that I can see (/rel, grab rams or repair wood, port) as if you wanted to suicide to the house you'd just bind in GH and grab a guildhouse port.  Don't see the merrits on this besides that but I'll tentatively put it on &quot;the list&quot; as I can see that being desired.<br>
<br>
Bindstone (cottage) - 1plat<br>
net: 1plat, 900g<br>
(opt 5plat, 400g)<br>
<br>
Vaults!<br>
There is currently 1 vault in the guild house that everyone has put/take rights on.  Our guild vault will be put in there soon as we get this all straightened out and get an albion vault NPC.<br>
<br>
1 vault needs to be in the cottage for a siege locker and quick turn-around.<br>
<br>
There is space for another vault in the house but as yet I can't think of a need for it unless we want to make a 'deposite for salvage' vault or something, for ease of donation to the guild...(not even sure if that makes sense but if we did that at all then we'd have to worry about the wrong things /salved from the guild vault...maybe...suggestions on the need of a 2nd guild vault in the house?)<br>
<br>
cottage-&gt; 1plat<br>
<br>
net 2plat, 900g<br>
(opt 6plat, 400g)<br>
<br>
<br>
Tools!<br>
Forge (have it)<br>
Spellcraft table) 0 cost to guild, donation<br>
Lathe: 1plat<br>
<br>
net 3plat, 900g<br>
(opt 7plat, 400g)<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, with our current fund, we can cover the opt price by a hair, but can easily cover the net price.<br>
<br>
Decorations....<br>
<br>
Frankly, I feel we need a porch...the house just looks odd w/o it.<br>
<br>
Porch deed, 500 gold <br>
<br>
I'd kill for some trees too <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
<br>
Now inside/outside decorating is going to be a challange.  Just with three folks helping me setup my 'office' it got more than a little confusing at times.<br>
<br>
Dunno if we should set a budget for decorating or maybe a special fund for it...  Just on the office I setup, I spent 1.5plat -- now, agreed, I don't do spartin well but we could easily drop some heavy cash on decorations.  The restriction on number of items can kill ya hard too so I'm sure some rearranging will need to be done.<br>
<br>
Now we can go slow or fast on decorations and if we find we don't like something, it sells back for the same price so no loss if we change our minds.  One thing to note, however, is that while woodworking has some items that can be made, they are only larger/smaller versions of what you buy anyway.  First you buy &quot;it&quot; then get materials to modify &quot;it&quot;.  No making it yourself and saving on price -- can you say Albion learned from Microsoft's marketing techniques?<br>
<br>
ANYway, the former SE folks have en masse RvR on Thursdays, we do it on Fridays so..how's Saturday for our meeting/mouse-warming?<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
(That's not a type-o, either.  We tailors take care of those who helped us get to LGM status and I just can't stand it to see a mouse freeze)<br>
